data.content:
MSTest has a dedicated `CollectionAssert` class and better assertion methods. Your current approach using `Assert.IsTrue` everywhere gives poor failure messages (just "expected true, got false").

Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Clear count check with meaningful failure message
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Verify all users are active
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    // Check a specific element exists
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"), "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

- **`Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual)`** — on failure reports *both* values, replacing your `Count > 0` and `Count == 3` checks
- **`CollectionAssert`** — useful for more structural checks:
  - `CollectionAssert.AllAreSatisfying(users, u => Assert.IsTrue(u.IsActive))` (.NET 8+)
  - `CollectionAssert.Contains(list, item)` — membership check
  - `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` — same items, any order
  - `CollectionAssert.AllAreNotNull(list)` — no nulls
- **Always add a message string** to `Assert.IsTrue` when the condition isn't self-describing
- **Avoid `users.Single()` in tests** — it throws `InvalidOperationException` instead of a test assertion failure, making diagnostics harder. Use `Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(...))` or `Assert.AreEqual(1, users.Count(...))` instead
